{
  "topicId": "m7-t1",
  "title": "Talking About Habits and Routines in Darija",
  "dialect": "darija",
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Introduction to the Present Tense (K- Prefix)",
          "arabic": "تقديم الفعل المضارع (سابقة الـ كـ)"
        },
        "text": "In Darija, to talk about actions you do regularly or habitually (like daily routines), we use the present tense. A key feature of the Darija present tense is the prefix 'كـ' (k-) or 'كايـ' (kay-) added to the verb stem. This prefix indicates that the action is ongoing or habitual. We'll start with the base form of the verb without the 'k-' prefix, then show how to add it.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "أنا كندير",
            "english": "I do / I make",
            "transliteration": "Ana kandir"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هو كايدير",
            "english": "He does / He makes",
            "transliteration": "Huwa kaydir"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هي كدير",
            "english": "She does / She makes",
            "transliteration": "Hiya katdir"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Verb: To Do / To Make (دار)",
          "arabic": "فعل: دار (عمل / صنع)"
        },
        "text": "The verb 'دار' (dar) means 'to do' or 'to make'. It's very common and can be used for many actions. Let's see its present tense conjugation with the 'k-' prefix.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "أنا كندير",
            "english": "I do / I make",
            "transliteration": "Ana kandir"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نتا كدير",
            "english": "You (masc.) do / make",
            "transliteration": "Nta katdir"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نتي كديري",
            "english": "You (fem.) do / make",
            "transliteration": "Nti katdiri"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هو كايدير",
            "english": "He does / makes",
            "transliteration": "Huwa kaydir"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هي كدير",
            "english": "She does / makes",
            "transliteration": "Hiya katdir"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "حنا كنديرو",
            "english": "We do / make",
            "transliteration": "Hna kandiru"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نتوما كديرو",
            "english": "You (plural) do / make",
            "transliteration": "Ntuma katdiru"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هما كايديرو",
            "english": "They do / make",
            "transliteration": "Huma kaydiru"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Verb: To Go (مشى)",
          "arabic": "فعل: مشى (ذهب)"
        },
        "text": "Another essential verb for daily routines is 'مشى' (msha), meaning 'to go'. Here's its present tense conjugation. Notice the 'm' sound at the beginning of the stem.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "أنا كنمشي",
            "english": "I go",
            "transliteration": "Ana kanmshi"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نتا كتمشي",
            "english": "You (masc.) go",
            "transliteration": "Nta katmshi"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هي كتمشي",
            "english": "She goes",
            "transliteration": "Hiya katmshi"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هما كايمشيو",
            "english": "They go",
            "transliteration": "Huma kaymshiw"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
